Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

In this project I will use a TMBD dataset, The Movie Database (TMDb), that contains information about more than 10 000 movies all over the years since 1960 and until 2015.

The original dataset has 21 columns: id - unique identification of each movie, imdb_id, popularity, budget, revenue, original_title, cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, runtime, genres, production_companies, release_date, vote_count, vote_average, release_year, budget_adj and revenue_adj - budget and revenue in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

During the project I will analyse the columns and do several changes in order to clean data and make it useful for the analysis. I will also create new dataframes and relate them with the origininal. All steps of the cleaning and analysis of the data will be explained along the project.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. Which variables affect the popularity of a movie?
  2. Movies release per year?
  3. What is the impact of genres in the movies statistics?
  4. Top 5 in movies?
  5. Budget vs Revenue?

Data Cleaning¶

After looking at the data I noticed that it's needed to perform several cleaning steps:

  • drop duplicates (there are two lines that are equal),
  • drop columns that will not be used in the analysis,
  • adress the null values,
  • fix inconsistencies in "release_date", "runtime", "budget" and "revenue",
  • fix data type in the "release_date" column,
  • create a calculated column: profit
  • create new dataframes for the columns that have several data in the same cell: "director", "genres" and "production_companies"

Drop Duplicates:¶

In [162]:
movies.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
In [163]:
movies.duplicated().sum()

0

Drop columns that will not be considered in the project:¶

The columns: "homepage", "tagline", "keywords","overview", "imdb_id", "budget", "revenue" and "vote_count" will not be subject of analysis so they will be dropped.

The "budget" and "revenue" columns won't be used in this project because I'll use the "budget_adj" ad "revebue_adj" and rename them to "budget" and "revenue":

In [164]:
movies.drop(labels=["homepage", "tagline", "keywords","overview","imdb_id","budget","revenue","vote_count"], axis="columns", inplace=True)
In [165]:
movies.rename(columns = {"revenue_adj":'revenue', "budget_adj" : "budget"}, inplace=True)

As seen above, when I filter release_dates after 2023-12-31 and which are impossible, I obtained several rows with dates of 2066, 2072, but in those rows, the "release_year" is for example 1966 and 1972. I concluded it was a mistake with the data column "release_date" and I'll fix it in the code line below:

In [183]:
aux_df = movies.loc[movies["release_date"] > "2023-12-31", :]
movies.loc[movies["release_date"]> "2023-12-31", "release_date"] = pd.to_datetime(aux_df["release_year"].astype(str).str.cat(aux_df["release_date"].dt.month.astype(str), sep="-").str.cat(aux_df["release_date"].dt.day.astype(str), sep="-"))

# Create a function to create a plot to avoid repetitive code:

def myplot(df, kind_plot, xvar, yvar, xlab,ylab,title, color):
    
    # Plot:
    df.plot(kind=kind_plot, x=xvar, y=yvar, figsize=[10,5], color=color);

    # Add x label and format it:
    plt.xlabel(xlab, size=10, fontweight="bold")
    # Add y label and format it:
    plt.ylabel(ylab, size=10, fontweight="bold")
    # Add title and format it:
    plt.title(title, size=12, fontweight = "bold");
   
    # Add legend:
    plt.legend()

1.3) Correlations:¶

I will study the relatioship between popularity and other variables using scatter plots.

In [220]:
# Create a function to create a scatterplot to avoid repetitive code:

def scatterplot(df, xvar, yvar, units_x, units_y, color):
    
    # Calculate correlation:
    corr = df[[xvar, yvar]].corr().iloc[0,1]
    
    # Plot:
    df.plot(kind="scatter", x=xvar, y=yvar, s=6, label=f'Correlation:{corr:0.3f}', figsize=[14,6], color=color)
    
    # Tidy up labels:
    xvar=xvar.replace("_"," ").title() #replace _ with a space and capitalize the first character
    yvar=yvar.replace("_"," ").title() #replace _ with a space and capitalize the firrst character
   
    # Add title and format it:
    plt.title(f'Relashionship between {yvar} and {xvar}'.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = "bold")
    
    # Add x label and format it:
    # I use an if statetment so that if I don't want to show units in the x label the "()" doesn't appear
    if units_x == "":
        plt.xlabel(f'{xvar} {units_x}', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
    else:
        plt.xlabel(f'{xvar} ({units_x})', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
    # The same for y labels:
    if units_y == "":
        plt.ylabel(f'{yvar} {units_y}', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
    else:
        plt.ylabel(f'{yvar} ({units_y})', fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
   
    # Add legend:
    plt.legend()
In [ ]:

Conclusions¶

The conclusions have been indicated along the analysis of the data. The main points are:

Popularity has had ups and downs over the years but most recentyly there is an increase in populariry levels, maybe because of digitalization and social networks that are very useful to promote movies. The most popular genre of all times is Adventure and I didn't find any strong correlation between popularity and other variables, although there is a moderate positive correlation between popularity and revenue and profit. The most popular movies are: Jurassic World, Mad Max: Fury Road, Interstellar, Guardians of the Galaxy and Insurgent.

The number of movies released per increased over time but more significantly from 2005/2006. By contrary, in terms of vote average and profit this tendency is not observed, and we can see a decrease over time.

The most released genre is Drama, followed by Comedy and Thriller but the most profitable is Animation. The genre with better ratings is Documentary, although is one of the less populars.

In terms of more release movies, I found the following top 5:

  • Directos: Woody Allen, Clint Eastwood, Martin Scorsese, Steven Spielberg and Ridley Scott.
  • Production companies: Universal Pictures, Warner Bros., Paramount Pictures, Twentieth Century Fox Film Corporation and Columbia Pictures.
  • Actors: Robert de Niro, Samuel L.Jackson, Bruce Wilis, Nicolas Cage and Miachael Caine.

In terms of financial results, the top 5 are:

  • Biggest Budget: The Warrior's Way, Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides, Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End, Superman Returns and Titanic.
  • Biggest Renevue: Avatar, Star Wars, Titanic, The Exorcist and Jaws.

I found a moderate positive correlation between budget and revenue.

Limitations of the dataset:¶

The original dataset has more than 10865 different rows. However there are issues with the data because almost 7000 rows have zero in the budget or revenue column. These data represents more than 60% of the original data and can not be used in the statistical analysis like correlations.

There is also lack of information about some data, for example popularity (how it was measured and units?).

For further analysis it would be interesting to add more complexity to the data, and have more information about revenues and budgets missing.
